{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017pbLNcLh2MdizDiGwt1mCM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the current state. Let me summarize what I've found:\n\n1. **Controller Version**: `v1.14.1` (registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:v1.14.1@sha256:f95a79b85fb93ac3de752c71a5c27d5ceae10a18b61904dec224c1c6a4581e47)\n   - nginx version: nginx/1.27.1\n   - Running in Kubernetes v1.31.0\n\n2. **Controller Args** (non-default/custom):\nMost of the arguments are standard configuration—election ID for leader selection, controller class and ingress class definitions, configmap reference for settings, and webhook certificate paths. The notable one is `watch-ingress-without-class=true`, which means the controller is monitoring ingress resources even if they don't explicitly specify an ingress class.\n\nWait, I'm noticing something odd in the live spec—it has both `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` and `--watch-ingress-without-class=false` listed, with false being the last one, so that's what actually takes effect. There's also `--publish-status-address=localhost`, which is non-standard and sets the ingress status to localhost instead of the actual service address. So the real non-default settings are `watch-ingress-without-class=false` and the localhost publish address.\n\nLooking at the ConfigMap for the controller, it's essentially empty with no custom data. Then there are three IngressClass resources defined: `ingress-1` and `ingress-2` each point to their own controller classes, while `nginx` points to `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1`—but the controller itself is configured with `--controller-class=k8s.io/ingress-nginx`, which doesn't match any of these IngressClass definitions.\n\nThe logs confirm this mismatch: all three IngressClasses are being ignored because none of them actually has the controller class the ingress controller is looking for. In the demo namespace, there are no Ingress resources at all, just a demo-app deployment.\n\nLooking at the ValidatingWebhookConfiguration for ingress-nginx-admission, it's set to fail on validation errors and validates ingresses during creation and updates. The deployment itself is configured with instant termination (no graceful shutdown period), allows one pod to be unavailable during rolling updates, uses direct host networking on ports 80 and 443, has tolerations for control-plane nodes, and is running as a single replica with a revision history limit of 10. The ingress-nginx-controller Service is also part of this setup.\n\nThe key non-standard configurations worth documenting are the `--watch-ingress-without-class=false` flag (which overrides the default true value, though there's a duplicate flag issue), the `--publish-status-address=localhost` setting for bare-metal/kind environments, a mismatch between the IngressClass name `nginx` and the controller name `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1` instead of the expected `k8s.io/ingress-nginx`, the zero termination grace period, an empty ConfigMap with no custom nginx tuning, and the use of hostPort for direct traffic routing.\n\nI also need to account for the validating webhook with a fail-closed policy. Now I'm mapping out the upgrade strategy, which should include assessing the current state, backing up the configuration, checking for version compatibility issues, fixing the IngressClass controller mismatch, resolving the duplicate flag problem, updating the controller image, adjusting the ConfigMap if necessary, running post-upgrade verification, and preparing a rollback procedure. The most critical issue to address is that all three IngressClasses are being ignored because their controller references don't match what the actual controller is using—the `nginx` class points to `k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1` but the controller identifies itself as `k8s.io/ingress-nginx`, so this needs to be corrected during the upgrade. achable, the Ingress CREATE/UPDATE operations will fail, which could block new Ingress creation during the upgrade process. Now I'm putting together a plan to address these issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4126,"cache_read_input_tokens":37937,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4126},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a0224061-bf49-491a-8f41-89d80269873e","uuid":"5db4009d-55ec-4f8b-bd34-3b0c8c923b28","request_id":"req_011CcRMAvs7uCmvZWV3JZTgL"}
